"Hold him still."
  "I'm trying to but the fucker won't- ARGH-"
  "Jackson!"
  "I got him, I got him."
  "Come on Roberts we haven't got all fuckin day."
  Rain fell on the leaves, launching them down to us like yellow sky-
boats as we held the child against the ugly wall of the stable. The
playschool tinkle of a distant ice cream van transformed the glinting 
metal gun from an adult's toy to a shocking instrument of fear.
  "In his eye, Roberts."
  "The knackers, man, not the eye! You'll blind him."
  "You think I care Peterson?"
  "Shut up." I snapped, streaks of cold water rushing down my face. I 
put the barrell against the child's forehead and added pressure. A 
circle of white appeared.
  "What's in it?" Jackson wanted to know. He was always worried about 
something. "It's not darts is it?"
  "Just keep your cake-hole shut, Jackson." said Smith, always the 
most irritable of the three. I hated the lot of them really, but they 
were very good, very quick and efficient. I couldn't argue there. 
They'd caught this fuckface of a child jamming lit fireworks in 
first-year-girls' pockets.
  "Take your hand off his mouth." I demanded.
  "He'll scream, man." Peterson looked around worriedly. "The 
fucker'll scream like mad, I betcha."
  "Take your hand off his mouth." I repeated urgently.
  The hand slipped away. From that moment on I was standing against 
the wall of an old, abandoned stable - one in which my mother had 
kept her horse when she was little - with a very realistic-looking 
gun held at point blank range against a captured bully's forehead. My 
glasses had gone, not just because of the rain (identity, 
recognition) and I was wearing a black coat I'd found in the bins at 
school. It stunk like shit, but that was my full intention.
  "Don't..." trembled the boy, his eyes full of terror. I could see 
how utterly petrified he was: to him the gun I held was /real/ and if 
I pulled the trigger his brains would blast out of the back of his 
head and slide down the wall.
  "You want to hurt," I told him. I did a different speech every 
time, just to make sure the others didn't lose interest. They were in 
it for the violence, the airguns and the chases, but they also found 
my words intriguing.
  "Do you want some money?" the kid offered, white bubbles of spit 
forming at the corners of his lips. "I can get you money. Do you know 
my sister? She's a fifth former, I can get you in bed with her. I can 
get you loads of stuff, gimme a chance."
  "What a sick fadge." Jackson cried.
  "Filthy twat," Smith agreed, slapping the kid around the mouth. "We 
think your sister's a slut, so keep your mouth closed, fuck-o."
  I fired the gun. The boy screamed.
  "Shit!" Peterson hissed, bending at the knees. "Oh man, I bet that 
went right into his fuckin skull!"
  "Roberts, what've you done?"
  "/Jesus/."
  I pulled the gun away. A small, round, plastic pellet had fixed 
firmly into the child's skin. Blood was forming around the edges. 
  "Get it out-"
  "/Leave it/," I shouted, pocketing the gun, bringing out a pen-
knife. "Lift up his jumper."
  "WHAT?"
  "Lift up his fucking jumper, /now/."
  "Roberts-"
  "I want to see his stomach."
  The kid started to bawl. Jackson paced up and down, looking up at 
the rain clouds as though wishing God would intervine.
  Peterson and Smith held the child's jumper up whilst I stepped 
forwards with a shining blade. Immediately there was a struggle.
  "Keep him still."
  "I'm trying man, I'm trying-"
  "Don't cut him, Roberts-"
  "No, don't."
  They secured him again, this time by holding his head back by the 
hair... and... and...   
  part of me wanted     
         to drop to my knees and beg for 
      forgiveness 
   for putting 
         a child through such 
                a nightmarish ordeal
         And the other part... it wanted to keep going... just a 
little longer, just to make sure-
  /I MUST MAKE SURE I MUST MAKE SURE I MUST MAKE-/
  "I'm going to cut your belly wide open," I whispered, close to 
tears. "You're going to reach down with your hands and run your 
fingers through your own guts, do you understand?"
  "No." was the thick, stunned reply. 
  "Are you ready? You'll hear me cutting. It sounds like a zip. 
Doesn'it Peterson?"
  "Wha..?" Peterson blinked and slipped his tongue back in. "Er, 
yeah. Like a zip. /Zzzzzzzzzzzzup!/" he cackled.
  "After three. Smith? Are you ready to catch the lad's innards?"
   Smith nodded, seeing my wink.
  "One..."
  "No, please I beg you don't do that it'll hurt-"
  "Two..."
  "-don't want you to do it-"
  "/Three/."
  I pressed the cold blade sideways against the child's stomach, and 
Jackson zipped up his coat. The three of them laughed. I nearly puked.
  "Let him go." I wheezed, squeezing my neck.
  They released the boy, kicking him up the arse several times in the 
