   they held a party in the sports centre on the last day before the 
summer holidays. All afternoon. What few remaining friends I had went
home. I stayed... sat up to a table full of rainbow-coloured glasses
at the edge of the dance floor.
  "Hey, gorgeous!" someone shouted. I stopped twirling the straw in my
fizzy orange and glanced up. I didn't recognise the girl who'd shouted
so I lowered my eyes again and carried on playing with my drink.
  They sat around me. Four of them. Smelling of purfume and chewing 
gum and lemonade and shampoo. I watched the bubbles in the orange 
juice rise and explode.
  "Carl innit?" one of the girls asked another, who nodded and faced 
the empty dancefloor, which was alive with rushing circles of coloured
light. I could tell Charlie had been releaved of his job as the Dj - 
the music at the moment was plain old dance, and he hated the fucking
stuff. Nobody was dancing anyway.
  "Are you okay?" the girl who'd seated herself beside me shouted in 
my ear. I turned my head and smiled a bit. She was plastered up to 
the eyeballs with make-up. In fact it made her look quite silly.
(whether this was her intention I wasn't too sure). She was wearing a 
pink tee-shirt that looked too small for her, and red jeans with 
lollypops and sweet-wrappers sticking out of all pockets.
  "Headache," I shouted back, tapping my head and grinning. The girl 
laughed hysterically and looked at her friends. They laughed too. `If 
making girls laugh is /this/ easy,' I remember thinking, `hell, I've 
not got much to worry about.'
  "D'you want to be the first to use this floor?"
  I shook my head.
  "Oh come oooon," she gave me a nudge. I blushed a bit.
  "Nah, can't dance to save my life."
  "I'll show you."
  "Yeah, right," I took swig of orange.
  "No-o, I'm being serious!" she dragged me off my chair, giggling 
like mad, until I gave in and stood against her. She was about a foot 
smaller than me, but didn't seem to mind. Her hands were small and 
cold and she felt too young, too fragile, but we wandered across the 
floor moving ourselves like crazy and lashing our heads around. 
  Three other couples joined in, then a guy on his own, then a 
teacher. After about three minutes, the music cut out and everyone 
moaned. I took the opportunity to go wheezing back to my chair.
  "Can't dance!" she sat next to me, closer than I would have liked. 
Her obviously-impressed friends leaned across the table and started 
asking me questions like, "what's your last name", "what class are you
in", "where do you hang out", "what's your favourite song". I did my
best to answer them but they never seemed satisfied.
  "Who're you going out with?"
  "Nobody," was my answer to that. It always had been, and a part of 
me said it always would be.
  "D'you want to come to my party? Well, it's my sister's but you can 
come along if you want. I'd like you to, in fact."
  I smiled at her. "You're sweet." They all laughed at that, but it 
wasn't sarcastic or mock-laughter, it was real, friendly, happy 
laughter and I joined in, blushing like hell. "Sorry," I said and
pretended to smack my head against the wall.
  "I don't mind," she nudged me again. She seemed to enjoy doing 
that. Every nudge was becoming softer, nicer, too. "But aren't you 
going to ask me what my name is?"
  "Oh yeah." I sniggered, drinking the last of my orange. I swallowed 
a semi-melted ice cube and coughed. "What's your name?"
  "Gemma. That's Kate, Helen and Sam." They all said hello as if we'd 
only just met, even though two of them were in my class.
  "Hi." I returned the gesture, no eye-contact.
  "Do you want another drink?" she started jangling coins in her 
pockets. "I've got plenty cash."
  "No, thanks." I refused politely. "I should get going."
  "Hey wait," she stopped me from getting up. "Hey, what-what about 
my party? Don't you want to know where I live?"
  "Look," I moistened my lips. "I'd love to come, it sounds great, 
but I don't know whether I... I'll be able to make it." She wouldn't 
take no for an answer. Whilst I made up excuses, she obtained a scrap 
of paper from a friend and wrote down a date, her address and a 
telephone number on it. She gave it to me, opening my hand, closing 
it up again. "Can you get hold of any beer?"
  I shrugged. "Dunno, why?"
  She and her friends burst out laughing. "It's a /party/, Carl, 
that's why! We're gonna rock the house down and get pissed, it'll be 
a laugh. You'd better come, I'll be heart-broken if you don't."
  "We'll see." I said pocketing the scrap of paper. "But I must go, 
can I get past you please?"
  "Cost you." she teased.
  I sniggered, "What?"
  "Cost you." she lowered her voice. "Kiss me and I'll let you past."
  "Come on, Gemma, I don't even know you."
  "You're not getting past-" Before she could finish, I was up on the 
seat, then on the table. A glass toppled when I jumped down but didn't
smash.
  I didn't turn around, I just kept going, pushing through crowds of
people, heading to that bright green EXIT sign.
