                   the ground was yellow, the sky was deep, darkening 
blue, and the tree... the tree was black.
  I stood alone at the edge of the field, looking at it (talking to 
it) watching those last few red, beaten prisoner-leaves struggle in 
the wind. I swear I heard them squealing.
  The trunk of this giant began thickly, coarsely, with solid bark 
and deep, powerful roots. It rose as high as a house into the air, 
lashing out at either side like a frozen ink spillage.
  And down below - me, alone in my untucked school uniform, bag over 
my shoulder, dangling straps, sleeves and hair flickering like flames.
  "Nobody left!" I shouted, grinning.
  The tree blinked.
  ---so what?
  "You don't have to hate me! I'm never going back! I just wanted you 
to know that!"
  ---three years have passed, you are not a child. Of course you will 
not go back. What would be the point? An elderly couple live there 
now: the friend you once had no longer exists, just as your childhood 
no longer exists.
  "Or my friends."
  ---the last of them turned against you, did he?
  "Yes."
  I looked down at myself... the grey tie, the white shirt, the black 
trousers. What did it mean? I was afraid to leave school? Was a part 
of me so happy to be in that final, safe realm - sixth form - that it 
rendered me unable to step out of teenage life?
  ---you can cut yourself loose from this madness if you try, 
Roberts. You are trapped in your own dying world and the only way out 
is to forget. Write if you must, but for God's sake let go.
  "And do what? Turn to who?"
  ---you will find other friends. You have always been good at that. 
In the grown-up world, they don't all turn against you. Violence is 
more real, sex is more real, but gradually you will learn to accept 
that. It might take years, it might take decades, but you will become 
what could be classed as normal. You /will/.
  "What about... eighty-eight?"
  ---You will find somebody else! Somebody better, somebody who will 
/let/ you forget.
  "What if she comes-"
  ---/no/. Worlds cannot be crossed, and you are about to leave the 
one in which that memory is trapped. Do not forget the love, but 
forget /her/. Put your foot out of this dimension.
  "But," I shivered. "I feel so alone. There's nobody out there who 
likes me. I always end up on my own."
  ---There are many, but you must find them. I'm going to leave you 
now Roberts. I'm going to leave you.
  "I'm going to leave you... I'm going to-" I breathed out harshly, 
slamming my hand over my mouth. Had I been speaking to myself all this
time? Was I really insane?
  No! Fucking no no no no!
  I looked up at the tree again. It was ferociously alive but silent,
motionless... and most definitely speechless.
  Cold, tired, but in a new, slightly different world, I walked home.


