Lost in the night, ears throbbing,  looking past the tangled bodies of
lovers, the darkness between the spotlights open up and form the image
of someone I once knew.
  "Awright, Shrimpman, what're you doin' 'ere?" asked the semi-
stranger. The one who had never spoken to him before in a non-
intimidatory way.
  "Just sittin' 'round, hangin' out,  you  know, mate," I reply, 
mocking him at a level  he  could  never  understand,  "What're you 
doing with yourself these days?"
  "I'm  workin'  at  Smith   an'   Nephews,"  he  answers,  
surprisingly unthreateningly, as  if  my  being  there  proves  
something  about my character (dickhead, wimp, wanker)  I'd  been  
expected to reveal over the years.
  "How much?"
  "Three-fifty,"
  Not able to calculate what  he  is  saying  in the grungy, slow 
motiontrance of drunkeness, I nod and he goes on his way.
  The reserved friends (Dancing?  In a  nightclub?  No way, we just 
want to  talk:  Talk,  in  this  noise?   No,  make  a  fool  of  
yourself) stand/slide up and made their  way  to  the  dancefloor.  I 
join them, laughing at a joke I haven't heard yet.
  Wave arms, move legs, smile at people  I don't want to know, push 
past bodies who do not (yet) push  back.   Is  this fun or fantasy?  
Will I regret it tomorrow?  Do the pairs of people (tongue in cheek) 
care for each other because of who they are  or  what they are?  Will 
they walk past me?
  Making my way, exhausted (How long?  Five minutes?  An hour?) from 
the dancefloor I pass a girl I  knew.   Hands  on  my face, down my 
chest, down, but my friends have gone, and  I  go too (Where am I?  
Which way am I facing?  Where will I end up?)
  Sit down, beside somebody I have not seen before, singing the words 
