F a t a l   D e l i v e r y

Old Bert shuffled across the feed barn, his ever-present smouldering 
pipe leaving a thin trail of glowing smoke in the early-morning 
half-dark. Fred padded silently behind him, knowing that Bert's 
habitual clatterings and mumblings would rouse a few rats and mice 
from their refuges amongst the clutter round the feed bins. Fred was 
a typical farm cat - big and scrawny, cunning and aloof, belonging 
and beholden to no-one, he just WAS.
  Bert filled the buckets up and stood them in a row by the door and 
swept the loose feed back onto the heap. The broom echoed noisily 
against the metal sides of the feedbin, causing the pigeons pecking 
around by the door to flutter up to the safety of the nearby rooftop.
  "Mornin Bert," Joel the young foreman strode in. "They're s'posed 
to be delivering the winter bullock grub this week, is t'other bin 
empty?"
  "Hmph!" - Bert's grunt could have indicated anything, but Joel took
it as yes and continued on his way, leaving the old man to carry on 
in his own dependable unchanging fashion, same as he had done for as 
long as anyone on the place could remember.
  As Bert returned with the empty buckets he had an uneasy feeling he
was not alone in the barn, yet everything was quiet nothing had 
changed. 
  Fred sat by the door thoughtfully eyeing the pigeons scratching 
around by the bins. He stacked the buckets in the corner and ambled 
across to the  workshop. He was standing at the workbench, 
absentmindedly searching for a screwdriver when he was jolted back 
to reality by an unearthly screech - seemingly coming from the 
feed-barn. He stood, undecided as to what course of action to take, 
and was still wondering when Graham, the cowman, came running in - 
"Got a cow down in the yard, come'n gi' us a hand to roll her over, 
can yer!"
  The urgency in Graham's voice galvanised Bert into action, and 
stopping just to grab a wagon-rope off the hook by the door, he 
followed the younger man quickly up to the cow yard.
  The cow had managed to get herself under the end of the feedmanger, 
and was now firmly wedged there, unable to move. They arrived 
simultaneously with Joel. 
  "Bloody 'ell! Wotamess!, hang on, I'll go get the forklift 'n we'll 
hoik the manger out the way." 
  Bert shot down the road and returned thirty seconds later with the 
forklift with the pallet prongs on the front. In no time he had 
deftly raised the manger, allowing the others to drag the cow out and 
roll her over. 
  She sat on the concrete for a while before getting shakily to her 
feet.
  "Er'll be a bit wobbly f'r'abit, Graham - y'better keep a good eye 
on her." commented Bert. "still, coulda bin a lot wuss."

                                   *

Halfway across the feedbarn Fred stopped dead in his tracks. He stood
stockstill, back arched, hair standing on end staring towards the 
empty feed bins hissing and fizzing like a dowsed bonfire.
  "S'truth! Wass'matter wi' thee, Fred?" mumbled Bert as he crossed 
the barn with his load of feed-buckets, continuing across to the 
yard, leaving the cat to solve it's own problems.
  As the final bucketful of cake rattled noisily into the manger to be
quickly wolfed down by the last group of eager calves the chill 
morning air was shattered by the same unearthly screech that had come 
from seemingly nowhere a couple of days ago. 
  "What the hell was THAT?" exclaimed Joel climbing out of his tractor
at the end of the yard. Bert emitted the usual non-commital grunt.
"Sounds like it came from in the barn."
 The feed barn was it's familiar untidy self, nothing moving, 
nothing out of place - eerily peaceful.

                                   *

"You seen Fred s'mornin', Bert?" enquired Joel
  "Nope, wasn't around yesterday either," the old man replied "He'll 
come when he comes - that's his way."
  "Hmm. S'pect you're right. Not like him to disappear for long 
though."
  There was a sudden kerfuffle in the barn behind them. They turned to
see a shower of feathers floating gently to the ground in front of 
the empty feedbin as a couple of pigeons flew squarking with fear 
across the yard. 
  A strangled gasping sound came from the direction of the bin.

                                   *

Ten-thirty next day the bulk feed delivery lorry rumbled into the yard.
The driver leaned out of the window as Joel approached: "Ten ton of 
'Supergrow 20' " 
  "Yeah, s'right. In the big bin half way down the barn. S'all ready."
Joel sauntered off towards the workshop.
  The man backed the big vehical up to the barn with practised 
accuracy and uncoiled the long unloading pipe. He swung it over the 
side of the bin and returned to the controls in the cab to start the 
blower.
  Up in the cowyard Bert and Graham were busy blocking off the gap at 
the end of the manger. Graham finished hammering and stood back to 
view his handiwork.
  "Thassbetter, shouldn't get no more o' the silly buggers gettin'
'emselves wedged in THERE any more."
  "Don't bloody want to, either," commented Bert "Didn't do the ole 
gal a lotta good. She milkin OK?"
  "Knocked 'er back a bit, but she's comin back up again." Graham 
replied as he walked back down to the yard.
  In the distance, the drone of the feedwagon was suddenly 
interrupted by a strangled, high-pitched roar, the drone rose to a 
shrieking crescendo before cutting off with a sound of grinding metal.
  "S'truth, sounds like the blower's blown a gasket!"  
  The two men arrived at the yard gate in time to see the feedlorry 
hurtling down the lane at an impossible speed, lurching manically 
from side to side.
  Joel was standing, dazed, outside the feedbarn, his face ghostly white.
  "It's alive..." he stammered, staring at the second feedbin.
  "Huh?"
  "Soon as the grub went in, it went mad! S'got the driver..." 
Joel keeled over. 
  Inside the barn, everything had gone deathly quiet.  
  The silence was blown apart by a crash followed almost immediately
by an enormous explosion - the lorry had hit the bridge.
  "Oh God.." Joel struggled to his feet, and swayed unsteadily across
to the workshop, Bert helped him over to the bench.
  "Better phone the firebrigade and ambulance!" yelled Graham, running
up from the gate. "Wagon's gone over t'bridge and the dieseltank's 
gone up!"

                                   *
 
Earsplitting sirens rent the peaceful air of the quiet village as the
emergency services descended on the place en masse.
  A couple of hours later the big feedwagon was just a heap of 
charred, twisted metal in a field. There were two full feedbins in 
the barn and Joel was sitting on the couch with a mug of tea.
  The driver was never found, it was assumed he died in the crash.

                                   *

Bert shuffled across the barn. 
  Fred was conspicuous by his absence. A mouse ran popped out from 
behind some sacks and scuttled quickly away.
  Everything was sleepily normal.
  "S'no good, Jo' " said Bert wearily, returning with his feed-
buckets as Joel came into the barn. "They wont touch that new lot of 
grub."
  "Why? Wassamatter withit?"
  "Search me - looks OK, smells OK. But they wont even look at it."
  Joel went in to look at the offending feed. 
  "Can't see nowt wrong wi' it - I'll give the feed firm a ring, 
mebbe they can come up with something."

                                   *
                             
"Right, that's completely cleared that bloody stuff! Now lets hope the
next lot's better." Joel leant on his shovel as Bert backed the 
tractor round and deposited the last loadful of feed into the trailer 
outside.
  The two men stood looking at the now empty feedbin. A chill gust of 
wind swirled across the barn. 
  "Pretty damn wierd." commented Joel. 
  Bert just "hrmphed" through his unlit pipe.

                                   *
 
Next morning a fresh-faced young driver carefully swung a brand-new 
bulk feed delivery wagon into the farmyard.
 "In the second bin just inside that big door up there to the left," 
Joel pointed across the yard, as the driver handed him the delivery 
ticket. 
  "Right-oh."
  The blower-motor hummed up to speed and the feed whizzed noisily up 
the delivery pipe and over into the bin; the driver sat in his cab 
unconcernedly sipping a mug of coffee.
  Half an hour later the lorry edged slowly out of the yard and made 
its way slowly back up the lane. The driver noticed a wide gap in the 
fence and a big charred patch in the field by the bridge and wondered 
idly to himself what had happened there.

                                   *
 
Old Bert shuffled across the feed barn, his ever-present smouldering 
pipe leaving a thin trail of glowing smoke in the early-morning 
half-dark.
  He filled up the usual succession of feedbuckets and carried them 
down to the calf-yards, emptying them one by one into the long line 
of mangers. He stood watching for a moment as the animals hungrily 
wolfed down their breakfast, shaking his head as he picked up the 
buckets and made his way back to the barn.
 Everything was quiet and still, same as always.


