The trouble with Janet was that she was dumb. It made him smile a
little, because this was the umpteenth girl he'd been initially 
attracted to who then ended up being nothing but a shit-stick with a 
pretty face wrapped like plastic around it. Yes, Janet was dumb, and 
it showed whenever they talked. Lulls in conversation everytime he 
brought up the most interesting things he could think of. She didn't 
say "Wow, that's amazing!" like she was supposed to - no, she was 
dumb, so she didn't say anything. She just looked away bored, or 
stared into a sudden vacuum in front of them.
  Janet was dumb, which was why she was not interested in all the
things he liked to talk about. She was dumb, so she couldn't 
appreciate his unique sense of humour. Janet liked to have sex, 
that's what she liked best. Janet liked you to have a big car and 
drive her around. Take her to the nightclubs so she could dance with 
all the other guys there, dancing images bleached permanently onto 
his mind, so that when he was alone he'd have the time to play them 
all over in his head. Rewind, rewind, play. Rewind, rewind, play.
  This time it wasn't Janet, it was someone else, and this film was
black and white with age. No colour, no light - just the two of them 
dancing alone in the darkness, happily. This was not a club - there 
were no other guys - there was no one he had to watch Janet dance 
with. In this dark room Janet only danced with him. In this dark room 
he could hear her tinkling laughter as she floated around him. She 
was laughing at his jokes. In the dark room, though he could not see 
her face, he knew she was smiling because she was glad to be with 
him. He could not see but she was glad. Glad to be with him.
  Softly he spoke to her, and she listened. Her silhouette in the
black turned towards him, and behind the invisible mask she was 
wearing he saw her eyes look into his, and listen to what he said. 
The world doesn't matter anymore, he told her, we're all alone and 
there's no one to listen. He waited for the distant smile, he waited 
for her dark head to turn to the vacuum and banish him there with 
that one gesture. But before his wait was over, she caressed him on 
the cheek. She took hold of his face and, in the dark, she started to 
kiss him tenderly. Thoughtless, endless kiss that lasted forever 
because it was full of words that flooded into his head and resonated 
there for the rest of his life. You are not alone, she kissed into
him, look who's kissing you, baby, look. I'm here, and you're not 
alone, and you'll never be, oh, no, words, just, keep spinning, 
dizzily in his head, I love you again, and again, in the dark I 
cannot see but i love you yes! Wake up and see me, darling, you're 
not alone there's someone waiting for you here. Wake up and see.
  When he woke up, it was still dark, but he could see...behind the
darkness, behind the shroud, hiding and waiting, waiting and hiding. 
He crept to the flowing black curtains slowly, dreading the sounds 
his feet made as he tapped the floor quietly in his tiptoe. Dreading 
that he might scare her away. Somehow, the figure behind the curtain 
remained until he was right in front of her. He lifted his hands 
gingerly, to draw back the darkness, to see her face for once, for 
the first time. Suddenly he stoppped. Took his handkercheif out and 
dabbed his forehead. Had to look perfect. Combed his hair as best he 
could with his fingers, straightened the tie he was, for some reason, 
wearing over his t-shirt. Took a deep breath. Took hold of the 
curtains, and in a single gasp, they were parted and he stared into 
the face of the girl he loved more than anything in the world. Looked 
at the girl who loved him in the same way.
  The tie was straight, the hair combed back half-perfectly, as if
with the fingers. New beads of sweat lined his forehead, and dripped 
down it. He smiled back at himself, and stepped out. "Shocking, isn't 
it?" he smiled, and walked out of the front door and into a street 
wrought with a thousand natural professionals. He left himself 
standing there, mouth wide-open because all this time, it had been 
himself in the dark, understanding him, talking to him, laughing with 
him. Laughing at his jokes.
  Now that he'd been found out, there was nothing for him to do but
walk out of the door and into the rest of the world, where people 
would never know, and where people never had to see himself behind 
the curtains.
  In the rest of the world, people look for the curtains out of dark-
ness, and when they find them, they discover Janet waiting behind. 
  Janet waits, she doesn't walk out the front door.       


