obvious freedom of summer. Reaching up, she took the picture from the 
wall, and put it down in front of her.  She traced the familiar faces 
of her friends with her finger.  Moving over the smiles and laughter, 
ruined by a mad man's dream.  She remembered each of her friends' 
funerals all different and yet the same.  The weeping, the crying, 
the talk of the lives wasted and the whispers of the monstrosities 
that the deceased must have been put through before death.  Everyone 
knew about the marks, the cuts and the burns. 
  A drop of water landed on the photo encircling her picture with a 
salty halo. She didnt notice.  She held the photo and tore, ripping 
