H e l l o   M a r y l o u 

Hey-ey - watchit!" I jumped hastily to the right, narrowly avoiding 
an unwanted dip. The skinny heifer rubbed playfully against me as
walked along beside the river.
  Marylou was lucky to be alive - born the day before christmas, Ian 
the cowman had found her lying abandoned, half-frozen and plastered 
in shit, out in the yard. 
  "Here y'are - dunno if you can do anything with this," he grimaced 
as he plonked the filthy, bedraggled little object on the straw at my 
feet. "The cow just doesn't want to know..."
  The calf lay bemused for a couple of minutes, wide dark eyes trying
to make sense of the situation. She made an unsuccessful attempt at
standing up just as Ian returned with a bucket of milk. 
  "Think she must've fallen down the steps," he said "she doesn't 
seem too steady on her legs."
  This seemed to me to be something of an understatement; however, I
picked the calf up and she stood precariously against my legs. This
achievement breathed new life and confidence into the frail little
creature beside me and she promptly emitted a surprisingly hearty
bellow to indicate that her uncaring mother had neglected to feed her
and she expected someone to put that right - immediately.
 The tinny transistor on the shelf blared out a `golden oldie' - 
"Hello Marylou". The calf repeated her vociferous demand. 
  Marylou had arrived.

Two days later dawn broke on a thickly snow-blanketed, bright white 
world, so any thoughts of vet or knackers' yard as a destination for 
Marylou were erased. It was almost two weeks before she was able to 
get up unaided - though once upright she was pretty mobile. As ever, 
Mother Nature cared for her own: Marylou quickly grew a long, thick 
coat to keep out the bitter cold of what turned out to be the most 
freezing January this century. 
  Her appetite and intelligence seemed to be just that bit above 
average, as if to compensate for her physical shortcomings. By the 
time all the December-born calves were ready to go across to the big 
yard she was as strong and lively as the rest of the bunch. 

That spring the young stock were turned out early as both hay and 
straw had all but depleted. Unfortunately, no sooner had they all 
gone out than the weather turned to non-stop rain. By Easter weekend 
the Brooks had become one vast lake. 
  "Never rains but it pours!" observed George, the manager - somewhat 
unnecessarily, under the circumstances, as we all gazed disconsolately
at the leaden grey skies on Easter Sunday morning. "Them heifers down 
t'Brooks is all along the far end under t'wood. If the water gets any 
higher they're gonna be completely marooned, we'll try and drive them 
back along the headland and across to the gate."
 This sounded to me to be a somewhat optimistic plan - cattle are not
renowned for their amphibious ambitions. The bunch of heifers, 
Marylou amongst them, had no intention of moving from their rapidly-
shrinking island of mud, and even less intention of going anywhere 
together. 
   Half-way along a pair of pheasants flew up right under the feet of 
the leading animal, in a squawking, flapping explosion of feathery 
panic and thirty heifers launched out across the floods in thirty 
different directions.
  After what seemed like an eternity of floundering and splashing 
about, rattling feed-buckets, and shouting ourselves hoarse, we wound 
up with twenty-nine heifers and a tractor with a puncture on the dry 
land near the road. We re-counted. Several times. One animal short...
  Marylou.
  The temporary silence was shattered by a desperate bellow from 
somewhere across the expanse of muddy water which had until last week 
been a large grassy meadow.
  I climbed up on the gate and looked back towards the wood. It all 
looked still and wet. 
  Another bellow.
  I focussed on the source of the sound - it sounded very close to 
the swirling rush of the swollen river. Then I saw what I had dreaded:
a black and white head just above the water, fighting to stay afloat.
  "You got'ny ropes on yer tractor?" I called to Fred, the rotund and 
unflappable tractor-driver.
  "Coupla wagon ropes. Oh, and the harrow chain," came the reply.
George joined me on the gate as I pointed across the field, 
  "Stuck," I said, blankly.
  Fred squelched across with an armful of ropes, followed by Nathan,
the cowman, who was looking at his watch and muttering something 
about breakfast.
  "Oh shut-up, Nathe, you're always bloody hungry - you got worms or 
summat?" George took one of the ropes, "C'mon, or she's gonna be 
washed down t'bloody sea 'fore we get to 'er. This lot ain't gonna go 
nowhere," He gestured back towards the group of drenched heifers by 
the gate. "You better nip back and bring the Farmhand down, Fred, - 
we'll want the fork for that tractor wheel anyway."
  Fred strode off up the track, fumbling in his jacket pocket for a 
cigarette as he went.
  We splashed off across the floods towards the the stricken heifer, 
hoping she wouldn't panic as we approached. She didn't move as we 
reached her - further investigations revealed that this was because 
she was /unable/ to move - she was stuck fast in the thick black clay 
of the crumbled riverbank.
  It took almost half an hour to get a rope round her, just as Fred 
came churning out across the field with the loader. He parked on the 
nearest patch of almost-dry-land - just within reach if we tied two 
ropes together.
  "Right, take it /very/ steady Fred, we gotta just ease 'er out 
really gentle - okay." George gesticulated to Fred to ease forward.
  The stout wagon-rope pulled taut, Marylou stayed put.
  "'ang on!" said Nathan; he went and rummaged around in the hedge 
behind the loader, returning with a long fence-stake. He leaned 
across and drove it deep into the mud behind Marylou's backside. 
  "Try again, Fred!" yelled George.
  The rope creaked as we each held one side to keep it even. Nathan 
heaved on the stake. I looked at the knot joining the two ropes 
together and prayed.
  There was a gurgling squelch from the river as slowly but surely 
the evil dark mud relinquished its captive
  "Keep it steady Fred."  George gestured again.
  Very slowly we hauled the exhausted heifer free of the mud and 
across the water-logged ground to the safety of the headland.
  For what seemed an eternity Marylou was too shocked and exhausted to
even move. Fred lit yet another fag. "C'mon gal," Nathan prodded the 
prone animal gently with his boot "Y'ain't dead yet, ye jus /think/ 
y'are!"
  The heifer finally made an effort to get up - and failed - her back 
legs simply crumpled under her. George bent down and felt down the 
length of one leg - it was ice-cold and seemed to be completely 
devoid of feeling.
  "Can't feel no breaks though," he muttered and he turned to me. 
"Can you stay 'ere with 'er while we take the rest of 'em back up, 
then I reckon we'll have to put 'er on the plank and cart 'er 'ome."
  He didn't wait for me to answer. Fred revved the loader and they 
trundled off across to the gate. 
 
I reached down and rubbed Marylou's cold soggy ears "Silly mutt! Why 
couldntya 'a stayed on the dry, where we was drivin' ya?" She rubbed 
her head on my legs. 
  "Nemmind, we'll have ya back in the dry soon," I hoped that George 
was right and that she didn't have any internal injuries.
  It seemed like hours before I heard the sound of the loader 
chugging back down the track.
  Fred pulled up in front of Marylou and let the loader-arm, now with 
an old door roped across it, down onto the ground. We hauled the 
heifer onto her makeshift stretcher and Fred gently eased the arm 
upwards. 
  "You wanna ride with 'er? - she's one a' yer bloody pets, ain't 
she?" enquired George, with a grin. He always teased me about any 
calves that recieved "special attention", being of the opinion that 
sentiment had no place in profitable farming.
  I hopped on the muddy board beside Marylou and we trundled back 
across the field.

Three hours later the vet straightened up. He rubbed his back.
  "Must be gettin' old... Anyway, yeah, she'll be alright, that right 
leg's pretty badly twisted, but there's nuthin' broken. She'll hobble 
a bit f'r'awhile though - you best keep her on her own so she doesn't 
get knocked around."
  "S'okay, she can go in the calving yard fr'a week or two,there's 
nowt due to calve till next month. Give Jen an excuse to spoil the 
bloody thing even more!" George laughed as he closed the loosebox 
door.
  Life, however, is never /that/ simple, and two days later the vet 
was back - Marylou had developed pneumonia. "You trying to kill this 
animal off, or what?" he enquired with a smile as he returned from 
his car with a large syringe full of antibiotic. Marylou winced as he 
jabbed the needle into her backside. "Do ya good ol' gal," he said, 
pushing the plunger down. He turned to me: "I'll leave you enough for 
a couple more doses - I think we've caught it in time - she oughtta 
be back on track by the end of the week, give me a ring if she 
isn't." 

It was nearly two months before Marylou was fit - by which time the
weather had finally got its act together and the wet spring was 
turning into a hot dry summer.
  "I reckon that damn thing can go back down the Brooks with the 
others today," said George, gesturing towards Marylou "She's gettin' 
too used to 'avin' 'er own way all the time. We'll drive her down the 
track after Ian's fetched t'cows up fer milkin' s'afternoon."
  Marylou ambled down the dusty track - she could see the other 
heifers in the field and was impatient to join them. They clustered 
excitedly round the gate as we let her through, and there followed 
the usual pushing and shoving and racing around to decide just where 
the newcomer fitted into the herd scheme of things.

Later that evening I walked down to check that the heifers were all 
OK. They were all grazing contentedly along the riverbank - a very 
different scene from the swirling mudflats of a few months ago.
  As I climbed the gate the radio DJ intruded into my thoughts from my
Walkman headphones "-and for tonight's `golden oldie' we go way back 
to nineteen sixty-one and it's Ricky Nelson with `Hello Marylou'..."
  I glanced across at the ungainly-looking creature grazing a few 
yards away and laughed.


